lture, historiography, physical science, psychoanalysis, and political theory. Sabrovsky demonstrates how the extraordinary condition of modernity emerges from the debates conducted by the last representatives of medieval scholasticism in which nominalism defeated realism, and he resituates the results of this triumph of nominalism in the writings of Friedrich Nietzsche, Theodor Adorno, Walter Benjamin, and Georges Bataille, among others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aLanguage and languagesxPhilosophy. 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 0aNominalism. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Literature. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 20th Century .2bisacsh1 aBurdman, Javier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFenves, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847917040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438479170423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438479170/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles